03766nam a22004455i 9780228000211DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20202020xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280002117 a10.1515/97802280002112doi  a(DE-B1597)656335  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aLAW0680002bisacsh04a343/.7101432231 aLévesque, Pascal, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFrontline Justice :bThe Evolution and Reform of Summary Trials in the Canadian Armed Forces /cPascal Lévesque. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHuman Dimensions in Foreign Policy, Military Studies, and Security Studies00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tCanadian Armed Forces Rank Structure -- tGeneral Introduction -- tA Description of the Summary Trial -- tCharter Breaches -- tReasonably Available Alternatives -- tCan Breaches Be Demonstrably Justified under Section 1? -- tReform Proposals -- tTowards a Vanguard Justice -- tAppendices -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCompared with its civilian counterpart - which struggles with delays and uncertain results - summary military justice is efficient. From offence until outcome, 90 per cent of cases are dealt with in less than ninety days. The other side of the coin is that there is no right to representation by defence counsel, no transcript produced, and no appeal to a judge. Nine times out of ten, individuals are found guilty. For service members, consequences can include fines, reductions in rank, confinement, and sentences of up to thirty days in military jail, sometimes with a criminal conviction. Addressing important gaps in legal literature, Frontline Justice sets out to examine summary justice in Canada's military and to advocate for reform. Pascal Lévesque describes the origins, purposes, and features of the summary trial system in the Canadian Armed Forces. He then analyzes the system's benefits and flaws and the challenges it faces in maintaining discipline while respecting the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms. Lévesque determines that troubling aspects of the system, including the fact that lower and higher ranks are dealt with and punished differently, are clear indicators of a need for change. Criticizing current legislation, the book takes into account the latest developments in military law and jurisprudence to make concrete recommendations for an alternative model of military justice. A thought-provoking and balanced analysis, Frontline Justice seeks to remedy some of the more unfair and arcane proceedings of the Canadian military's summary trial system.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aLAW / Military.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228000211?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228000211423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228000211/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles